[recv] {"type": "message_start", "message": {"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_dDzbSogv6J0D0BWCimy3CB3R|fc_0dc59e3b6f8d5adb016a42a18045088195849b10363d5af223", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "\nKEY Getting Started\nad the bytecode and execute it directly in the running JVM.\n         \n\n         JANINO is integrated with Apache Commons JCI (\"Java Compiler Interface\") and JBoss Rules / Drools. \n\n         \n          JANINO can also be used for\n           static code analysis \n          or\n           code manipulation .\n         \n\n         Table of Contents \n         \n            Getting Started  \n            Properties  \n            Requirements  \n            Limitations  \n            License  \n           \n             Download \n             \n                Packages  \n                Security / integrity  \n                Installation  \n                Examples  \n             \n           \n           \n             Documentation \n             \n                Change Log  \n                JAVADOC  \n                Books  \n                Links  \n               \n                 \n\nKEY Maven\n      href=\"https://spdx.org/licenses/BSD-3-Clause.html\">New BSD License .\n         \n\n         \n              Download\n         \n\n         \n              Packages\n         \n\n         If you are using MAVEN, add this entry to your POM file: \n\n          \n&lt;dependency&gt;\n    &lt;groupId&gt;org.codehaus.janino&lt;/groupId&gt;\n    &lt;artifactId&gt;janino&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n    &lt;version&gt;***&lt;/version&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;  \n\n         \n \n     org.codehaus.janino   \n     janino \n     *** \n \n-->\n            &lt;  dependency  &gt;  \n            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  &lt;  groupId  &gt;org.codehaus.janino&lt;/  groupId  &gt;  \n            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbs\n\nKEY commons-compiler\n>\n         \n       \n     \n   \n \n\n         (Replace \"***\" with the latest version of JANINO.) \n\n         If you are not using MAVEN, do the following instead: \n\n         \n           \n            Download  the latest version of\n            \"janino- version .jar\" .\n           \n           \n            Download  the same version of\n            \"commons-compiler- version .jar\" .\n           \n           Put the two JAR files on your classpath. \n         \n\n         \n              Security / integrity\n         \n\n         \n          All packages are signed with one of these PGP keys. Make sure to check the package signatures to prevent\n          supply chain attacks:\n           \n           Key #1 \n           Key #2 \n           Key #3 \n         \n\n         \n              Installation\n         \n\n         \n          If you're using an IDE like ECLIPSE, you can optionally downl\n\nKEY Properties\nnning JVM.\n         \n\n         JANINO is integrated with Apache Commons JCI (\"Java Compiler Interface\") and JBoss Rules / Drools. \n\n         \n          JANINO can also be used for\n           static code analysis \n          or\n           code manipulation .\n         \n\n         Table of Contents \n         \n            Getting Started  \n            Properties  \n            Requirements  \n            Limitations  \n            License  \n           \n             Download \n             \n                Packages  \n                Security / integrity  \n                Installation  \n                Examples  \n             \n           \n           \n             Documentation \n             \n                Change Log  \n                JAVADOC  \n                Books  \n                Links  \n               \n                 Basic Examples \n                 \n    \n\nKEY Requirements\n with Apache Commons JCI (\"Java Compiler Interface\") and JBoss Rules / Drools. \n\n         \n          JANINO can also be used for\n           static code analysis \n          or\n           code manipulation .\n         \n\n         Table of Contents \n         \n            Getting Started  \n            Properties  \n            Requirements  \n            Limitations  \n            License  \n           \n             Download \n             \n                Packages  \n                Security / integrity  \n                Installation  \n                Examples  \n             \n           \n           \n             Documentation \n             \n                Change Log  \n                JAVADOC  \n                Books  \n                Links  \n               \n                 Basic Examples \n                 \n                   <a href=\"#janino-as-an-expression-evalua\n\nKEY SimpleCompiler\norg.codehaus.commons.compiler.samples.ClassBodyDemo '\n&gt; public static void\n&gt; main(String[] args) {\n&gt;     System.out.println(java.util.Arrays.asList(args));\n&gt; }' \\\n&gt; a b c\n[a, b, c]\n$  \n\n         \n              Janino as a Simple\n          Compiler\n         \n\n         \n          The  SimpleCompiler  compiles a single .java file (\"compilation unit\").\n          Opposed to normal Java compilation, that compilation unit may declare  more than one  public type.\n         \n        \n         Example: \n\n          \n// This is file \"Hello.java\", but it could have any name.\n\npublic\nclass Foo {\n\n    public static void\n    main(String[] args) {\n        new Bar().meth();\n    }\n}\n\npublic\nclass Bar {\n\n    public void\n    meth() {\n        System.out.println(\"HELLO!\");\n    }\n}  \n\n         It returns a  ClassLoader  from which you can retrieve the classes that were compiled. \n\n         To run this, type: \n\n          \n$ java -cp janino.jar:commons-compiler.jar \\\n&gt; org.codehaus.janino.SimpleCompiler -help\nUsage:\n    org.codehaus.janino.SimpleCompiler &lt;source-file&gt; &lt;class-name&gt; { &lt;argument&gt; }\nReads a c\n\nKEY ExpressionEvaluator\nlike ECLIPSE, you can optionally download \"janino- version -sources.jar\" and\n          \"commons-compiler- version -sources.jar\" and configure them as the source attachments. That'll\n          get you tooltip JAVADOC and source level debugging into the JANINO libraries.\n         \n\n         Use one of the features, e.g. the \"expression evaluator\", in your program: \n\n          \nimport org.codehaus.janino.*;\n\nExpressionEvaluator ee = new ExpressionEvaluator();\nee.cook(\"3 + 4\");\nSystem.out.println(ee.evaluate()); // Prints \"7\".  \n\n         Compile, run, ... be happy! \n\n         \n              Examples\n         \n\n         \n          The  ShippingCost \n          class demonstrates how easy it is to use Janino as an expression evaluator.\n         \n\n         \n          The  ExpressionDemo \n          class implements a command line-based test environment for the expression evaluator.\n         \n\n         \n          The <a\n  \n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782751617438}}
